<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Spare SPAC money</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjIvc3BhY3Mtd2FudC10aGVpci1tb25leS1iYWNrP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDAyMjQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB93e92c11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">talked on Wednesday</a>=C2=A0about an unusual=C2=A0=
situation at a couple of special purpose acquisition companies. Basically a=
 SPAC raises money by selling stock to public shareholders at $10 per share=
, puts the money in a trust account, and then either (1) uses the money to =
merge with a private company, taking it public and giving the public shareh=
olders shares in that newly public target company, or (2) fails to do a mer=
ger within two years and gives the shareholders their $10 back with interes=
t. The sponsor of the SPAC generally pays the expenses of starting the SPAC=
 and looking for a deal; if she finds a deal she is richly rewarded (with 2=
0% of the SPAC=E2=80=99s shares), but if she doesn=E2=80=99t she eats those=
 costs. The trust account can=E2=80=99t be touched to pay those costs; it i=
s there to be used only if the SPAC finds a deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What we talked about Wednesday was the edge ca=
se in which a SPAC does not do a deal and somehow incurs expenses that the =
sponsor does not pay. In that case, it seems that the SPAC can ask the publ=
ic shareholders to hand back some of the money that they got: The company r=
eally had to pay that money to its vendors before it paid the shareholders,=
 and so the=C2=A0shareholders seem to be technically liable for paying it b=
ack. Or so the SPACs say anyway. In practice the numbers involved are small=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0$0.02 or $0.11 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it seems unlike=
ly that the SPACs will pursue every retail shareholder to the ends of the e=
arth for, like, $11 each. Also, I mean, the sponsor really=C2=A0<em>should=
=C2=A0</em>bear these expenses. But, right, technically, if you invest in a=
 SPAC and it somehow ends up with (1) no deal, (2) your $10 per share plus =
interest in a trust account, and (3) a=C2=A0<em>negative=C2=A0</em>amount o=
f money in its=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>accounts, then I guess you could ha=
ve to make up the difference.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what about the opposite edge case? What ab=
out a SPAC that ends up with (1) no deal, (2) your $10 per share plus inter=
est in a trust account, and (3) a=C2=A0<em>large positive=C2=A0</em>amount =
of money in its other accounts? Not, like, the sponsor puts in $10 million =
to cover expenses, there are $6 million of expenses, and there=E2=80=99s $4=
 million left over: That=E2=80=99s an easy case; the sponsor gets the $4 mi=
llion back, and you only get your $10 plus interest. But what if the sponso=
r puts in $10 million to cover expenses, and there are $10=C2=A0million of =
expenses, and then the sponsor trips over a cord in the SPAC=E2=80=99s offi=
ces and falls into a wall and there=E2=80=99s a $50 million=C2=A0stash of d=
iamonds behind the wall? The diamonds belong to the corporation (let=E2=80=
=99s say), but do all the shareholders get to share in their value? Or, if =
the SPAC doesn=E2=80=99t acquire a target, does the sponsor just hand the s=
hareholders back their $10 plus interest and keep the diamonds?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words: When the SPAC does not complet=
e a deal, are its public shareholders <em>real=C2=A0shareholders</em>, the =
residual claimants on the assets of the corporation, or are they=C2=A0<em>k=
ind of creditors</em>, entitled to get their $10 back with interest, no mor=
e, no less? Intuitively, the=C2=A0answer is kind of in between, isn=E2=80=
=99t it? In a legal sense the shareholders are shareholders. But their mone=
y is kept in trust for them, and there are lots of protections to try to pr=
event them from ending up getting back less than $10 per share, though as w=
e saw Wednesday those protections are not absolutely ironclad. But there ar=
e also provisions to prevent them from getting back=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em=
>than their $10 plus interest: When the SPAC winds up, generally, the publi=
c shareholders get redeemed at the amount in the trust, and the sponsor get=
s whatever is left.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the tripping-into-diamonds example is f=
anciful, but there is a real way that a SPAC can end up with no deal and a =
pile of cash: It can=C2=A0<em>sign=C2=A0</em>a deal with a target company, =
and then the target company can=C2=A0<em>get out of the deal=C2=A0</em>and=
=C2=A0<em>pay a breakup fee</em>. In general when a company signs a merger =
agreement =E2=80=94=C2=A0including with a SPAC =E2=80=94=C2=A0there will be=
 some provisions in the agreement that allow the target to get out of the d=
eal in some circumstances (for instance, if it gets a better offer), and if=
 that happens the target usually has to pay the acquirer a fee to terminate=
 the agreement. When the acquirer is a SPAC, it ends up with a bunch of cas=
h and no merger. Who gets the cash: the public shareholders, or the sponsor=
s?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This has happened a few times in the recent SP=
AC boom, and unsurprisingly the sponsors think they should keep the money. =
In February 2021, a SPAC called Fast Acquisition Corp. <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLm=
dvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTU3MzcvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMTQzNjYzL3RtMjEyM=
jM1My0yMV9kZWZtMTRhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1851c88e" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">signed=
 an agreement</a> to merge with Fertitta Entertainment Inc., the owner of t=
he Golden Nugget and Landry=E2=80=99s. In December 2021, Fertitta <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTgxNTczNy8wMDAxMjEz=
OTAwMjEwNjQ1OTAvZWExNTIxMjktOGtfZmFzdGFjcS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45=
13e0ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">called off the deal</a> and agreed to pay a breakup fee of =
$16 million, or $32 million if Fast Acquisition didn=E2=80=99t find another=
 deal. It didn=E2=80=99t, and in August 2022, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTU3MzcvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIyMDQ2NTE0L2VhMTY0MTQwZXg5OS=
0xX2Zhc3RhY3EuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfd84449a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it announced<=
/a> that it would redeem its shares for $10 plus interest, or about $10.02=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and the sponsor would keep the $32 million. Shareholde=
rs sued; from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3065=
1429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmR=
meElVL3JhcDhDVl9PZlQ0OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0fcd1a0b" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">thei=
r complaint</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SPAC explosion has led to its =
fair share of =E2=80=9Cfast ones=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0fiduciaries, but the Spon=
sor of FAST Acquisition Corp. may have topped them all:=C2=A0it is orchestr=
ating a theft in broad daylight of $23.7 million right out of the pockets o=
f the SPAC and its stockholders. The Sponsor, and its owners, which include=
 each of the SPAC=E2=80=99s officers and directors, failed to arrange a bus=
iness combination and now have decided to simply walk away with the SPAC=E2=
=80=99s only valuable asset=E2=80=94a termination fee it obtained after its=
 only potential deal fell through. A more flagrant breach of the duty of lo=
yalty can hardly be imagined.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe defendants believe the lawsuit is=
 without merit and intend to defend it vigorously,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
