<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of the story of the collapse of FTX Tradi=
ng Ltd. =E2=80=94=C2=A0the story that its now-indicted founder, Sam Bankman=
-Fried, told about it =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that FTX misplaced a few billion do=
llars of customer money due to an unfortunate but understandable mix-up. It=
 went like this, see. Early in its history, FTX had trouble opening bank ac=
counts, because banks were nervous about dealing with crypto exchanges. But=
 Alameda Research, Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s crypto trading firm,=C2=A0<em>di=
d=C2=A0</em>have access to banks, in part because crypto trading firms are =
less off-putting to banks than crypto exchanges are<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> and in part because =E2=80=9CAlameda Research=E2=80=9D is a vague name=
 that was chosen specifically to avoid scaring banks.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so when customers wanted to deposit money =
at FTX, FTX would sometimes tell them to wire the money to Alameda. Alameda=
 would get the money in its bank account, and would then tell FTX that it h=
ad received it, and then FTX would credit the money to the customer=E2=80=
=99s trading account. But <em>Alameda would keep the actual money</em>, in =
its bank account. To make things=C2=A0balance, FTX would record a liability=
 from Alameda to FTX in its internal accounts: It would make a little note,=
 like, =E2=80=9Cwe have credited $100 to Customer X=E2=80=99s account, but =
Alameda is holding the money for Customer X, so Alameda owes us that $100 a=
nd we should remember to get the money from Alameda at some point.=E2=80=9D=
 Over time this balance =E2=80=94=C2=A0the amount that Alameda was holding =
for other customers and owed to FTX =E2=80=94 grew to $8 billion. But also =
somehow FTX forgot about it? Basically FTX thought that Alameda had the $8 =
billion, and also that its customers had the $8 billion, so it thought ther=
e was $8 billion more on FTX than there was. FTX thought that it was well c=
apitalized and that Alameda was doing fine, because it forgot that there wa=
s a missing $8 billion. =E2=80=9CHidden, poorly internally labeled =E2=80=
=98fiat@=E2=80=99 account: -8,000,000,000,=E2=80=9D is a <a href=3D"https:/=
