seum=E2=80=99s nomination of directors to the Purple Board of Directors =E2=
=80=93 violates the Company=E2=80=99s charter, fundamentally transforms the=
 =E2=80=9Cone share, one vote=E2=80=9D structure used to elect Company dire=
ctors into a cumulative voting regime that prevents holders of a majority o=
f the common stock from electing or removing the full board, and is a bad f=
aith attempt by the Special Committee of Purple=E2=80=99s Board to entrench=
 itself and thwart shareholder democracy. Specifically, the preferred stock=
 issuance violates those provisions of the Company=E2=80=99s charter that l=
imit the form of stock distributions to holders of the Company=E2=80=99s Cl=
ass A shares to additional shares of Class A common stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Adam Gray, Managing Partner of Coliseum, said,=
 =E2=80=9CThe Purple Special Committee=E2=80=99s brazen action =E2=80=93 ta=
ken no more than 24 hours after Coliseum proposed five highly qualified can=
didates for election =E2=80=93 demonstrates the lengths to which the incumb=
ent non-executive directors will go to preserve their Board seats at the ex=
pense of stockholders. To seek such Board security amidst a contested elect=
ion =E2=80=93 and leveraging corporate machinations and stockholder resourc=
es to do so =E2=80=93 is further evidence that Board change is warranted. W=
hile Coliseum has sought to work constructively with the Purple Board =E2=
=80=93 consistent with the collaborative investment approach we have execut=
ed successfully for the past 15-plus years =E2=80=93 we have been left with=
 no choice but to take the extraordinary step of a proxy contest and filing=
 litigation seeking to ensure the election of directors is conducted in a f=
air and democratic manner for the benefit of all Purple stockholders.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3IxZ19TVW5lX2F6TS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B87bc8832" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>, which mostly makes the general point=
 that it is unfair for the board of directors to change shareholders=E2=80=
=99 voting rights:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The dividend issuance, which is designed solel=
y to prevent Coliseum from electing its nominees and removing existing dire=
ctors, violates the Company=E2=80=99s charter and was not justified by any =
conceivable threat to corporate policy or effectiveness. Where, as here, a =
board of directors =E2=80=9Cdeliberately employs various legal strategies t=
o either frustrate or completely disenfranchise a shareholder vote, =E2=80=
=A6 [t]here can be no dispute that such conduct violates Delaware law.=E2=
=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Board upset the reasonable and settled exp=
ectations of every stockholder that invested in Purple=E2=80=95namely, that=
 one share would equal one vote and that holders of a majority of the commo=
n stock would be empowered to replace the entire Board if they saw fit to d=
o so. This principle is fundamental to the legitimacy of a board. The struc=
ture imposed by the NED Defendants strikes at the heart of corporate democr=
acy and Purple stockholders=E2=80=99 expectations by=C2=A0empowering holder=
s of a comparatively small number of shares to block change at the Board le=
vel, even if the majority wants to replace the existing directors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know how this will play out. I=
n general my instinct is that if there is a technical trick that directors =
can use to issue voting shares, without directly changing anyone=E2=80=99s =
share of the vote, they can probably get away with it, but I have no idea. =
And there=C2=A0<em>has=C2=A0</em>been a glut of these things recently, push=
ing out the limits of what is possible; you could imagine Delaware courts s=
aying =E2=80=9Cno, that=E2=80=99s enough, stop it, just let your shareholde=
rs vote.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two more specific points here. One i=
s that Purple was apparently not, technically, allowed to <em>give </em>sha=
reholders the PRPLS. The way a company distributes securities to all of its=
 shareholders for free is through a <em>dividend</em>, a distribution of so=
me stuff (here, voting preferred stock) to each share of common stock. So l=
ast week <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.=
257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAw=
MTIxMzkwMDIzMDExMTM2L2VhMTczNTA5ZXg5OS0xX3B1cnBsZWlubi5odG0/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB1a1492e2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Purple announced</a> that it had =E2=80=9Cde=
clared a dividend new Proportional Representation Preferred Linked Stock (=
=E2=80=98PRPLS=E2=80=99) for each 100 shares of Purple common stock (=E2=80=
=98Common Stock=E2=80=99) owned by Purple=E2=80=99s shareholders.=E2=80=9D<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Coliseum argues that it is not allowed to =
pay a dividend of random sorts of stock: Purple=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30651429.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2V=
jLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDE5MDIyMTM4L2YxMH=
EwOTE5ZXgzLTFfcHVycGxlLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB905592a1" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> co=
rporate charter</a> says that =E2=80=9CStock dividends with respect to Clas=
s A Common Stock may be paid only with Class A Common Stock,=E2=80=9D and C=
oliseum points out that =E2=80=9Cthe dividend of Preferred Stock constitute=
s a =E2=80=98stock dividend=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D under=C2=A0Delaware law. I=E2=
=80=99m not sure that was what the charter=C2=A0<em>meant</em>, but it is w=
hat it=C2=A0<em>says</em>, so it=E2=80=99s a clever argument.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that Purple apparently did this d=
ividend=C2=A0<em>one day after=C2=A0</em>selling stock to Coliseum:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shockingly, the Preferred Issuance=
 came one day after a stock offering settled whereby Purple received from C=
oliseum $27 million in cash that Purple needed to facilitate an amendment t=
o its credit agreement to provide Purple with necessary flexibility and run=
way for growth. The [Non-Executive Director] Defendants knew as early as Ja=
nuary 17, 2023, that Coliseum considered nominating a new slate of=C2=A0dir=
ectors, and knew well in advance of the stock offering closing that they pl=
anned to authorize the Preferred Issuance if they received formal notice of=
 Coliseum=E2=80=99s slate. Nevertheless, the NED Defendants=E2=80=95acting =
in bad faith=E2=80=95allowed Coliseum (and other stockholders) to proceed w=
ith the stock offering without ever disclosing that they had crafted a dilu=
tive dividend that they were ready to and would deploy at a moment=E2=80=99=
s notice to fundamentally change the voting structure and prevent holders o=
f a majority of the common stock from replacing the entire Board.=C2=A0</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a weird relationship. Purple has a contr=
olling-ish shareholder, the shareholder wants to buy the company, and the b=
oard seems to dislike the shareholder. If you are the board in that situati=
on, you might try to mess with shareholder voting rights to contain the con=
trolling shareholder, but you might also have to hit that shareholder up fo=
r money. You want to get the timing right: You ask them for money=C2=A0<em>=
before=C2=A0</em>you cut off their voting rights.</p>
